aps_mkorbcov can be used to generate orbit0  files. The command needs arguments 
as follows:

aps_mkorbcov -h -p<platform> -P<projection> [-y<yaw>] -a<lat1> -o<lon1> -A<lat2> -O<lon2> -i<instrument> -d<duration> -m<smin> -s<ssec>


where....
 
        -h <help>
        -p <platform>   -- ers1_A .. ers1_G, ers2_A, R1, jers1_A
        -P <projection> -- (C) Cylindrical,(M) Mercator,(G) Globe
                           (N) North Pole ,(S) South Pole
        [-y <yaw>]      -- Yaw angle for N or S projections
        -a <lat1>       -- Latitude of upper left corner
        -o <lon1>       -- Longitude of upper left corner
        -A <lat1>       -- Latitude of lower right corner
        -O <lon1>       -- Longitude of lower right corner
 
           For projection C or M, lat1,lon1,lat2,lon2 are the two corners
           For projection N or S, only lat1 is needed but should be < 90
           For projection G, lat1 and lon1 is the center point, lat2 is
           used as axis tilt(default=0),lon2 is zoom factor (default=1)
 
        -i <instrument> -- ST1..ST7,WD1..WD3,FN1..FN5,EL1,EH1..EH6
                           SWA,SWB,SNA,SNB for R1, JERS-1/A for J1
                           ERS-1/A..ERS-1/G for E1, ERS-2/A for E2
        -d <duration>   -- r1,R2.. number of rev's
        -m <smin>       -- Step time, minutes
        -s <ssec>       -- Step time, seconds


The format of files generated by this program:

	sat.sensor.projection

	R1.SNA.C, ers1_G.ERS-1.G or J1.STD.M


There are tables for each sat which contain sensor information should be
in current directory:

	R1
	J1
	ers1_A
	ers1_B
	ers1_C
	ers1_D
	ers1_E
	ers1_F
	ers1_G
	ers2_A

There is script named "test" which I use to generate all sat with all
different sensors.
